  <subsection xml:id="subsec-cotangent-function">
    <title>The Cotangent Function</title>
    <p>
      Recall that the Quotient Identity (<xref ref="def_quotient-identities"/>) for the cotangent function is defined as
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>\cot x=\frac{\cos x}{\sin x}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      The denominator becomes zero when <m>\sin x=0</m>, corresponding to <m>x=\ldots,-\pi,0,\pi,2\pi,\ldots</m>. In general, <m>\cot x</m> is undefined for angles of the form <m>n\pi</m>, where <m>n</m> is an integer, leading to vertical asymptotes. Additionally, as we learned in <xref ref="subsec_periodic-functions"/> the cotangent function has a period of <m>\pi</m>. We can construct a plot for it in a manner similar to how we constructed the tangent function. This is illustrated in <xref ref="cotangent-graph-animation"/>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="cotangent-graph-animation">
      <caption>
        As <m>\theta</m> moves from <m>0^{\circ}</m> to <m>180^{\circ}</m>, this figure plots the values of <m>y = \cot \theta</m>. Note that while we will generally be using radians when graphing trigonometric functions, this figure uses degrees to help visualize the angle.
      </caption>
      <interactive geogebra="mhzmakps" aspect="1.75:0.75"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Plotting points for <m>y=\cot x</m> and using the fact that the cotangent function is periodic, we obtain the graph for cotangent in <xref ref="cot-graph-extended"/>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="cot-graph-extended">
      <caption>The plot for <m>y=\cot(x)</m>.</caption>
      <image xml:id="fig-cot-graph-extended">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
          \begin{axis}[
          axis lines=middle,clip=false,
          xmin=-2*pi-0.5,xmax=3*pi+0.5,ymin=-3.3,ymax=3.3,
          xtick={-5*pi/2,-3*pi/2,...,5*pi/2},
          xticklabels={\(-\frac{5\pi}{2}\),\(-\frac{3\pi}{2}\),\(-\frac{\pi}{2}\),\(\frac{\pi}{2}\),\(\frac{3\pi}{2}\),\(\frac{5\pi}{2}\)},
          xticklabel style={black},
          xlabel=\(x\),
          ylabel=\(y\)]
          \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi+0.3:-pi-0.3,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cot(deg(x))};
          \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-pi+0.3:0-0.3,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cot(deg(x))};
          \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=0+0.3:pi-0.3,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cot(deg(x))};
          \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=pi+0.3:2*pi-0.3,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cot(deg(x))};
          \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=2*pi+0.3:3*pi-0.3,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cot(deg(x))};
          \draw [dashed,red] (-2*pi,-3.3) -- (-2*pi,3.3) node[below,pos=0]{$x=-2\pi$};
          \draw [dashed,red] (-pi,-3.3) -- (-pi,3.3) node[above,pos=1]{$x=-\pi$};
          \draw [dashed,red] (0,-3.3) -- (0,3.3) node[below,pos=0]{$x=0$};
          \draw [dashed,red] (pi,-3.3) -- (pi,3.3) node[above,pos=1]{$x=\pi$};
          \draw [dashed,red] (2*pi,-3.3) -- (2*pi,3.3) node[below,pos=0]{$x=2\pi$};
          \draw [dashed,red] (3*pi,-3.3) -- (3*pi,3.3) node[above,pos=1]{$x=3\pi$};
          \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The symmetry of the cotangent function about the origin is evident, confirming its nature as an odd function, as explained in <xref ref="subsec_even-odd-trig-functions">Section</xref>.
    </p>

  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-cosecant-function">
    <title>The Cosecant Function</title>
    <p>
      Recall that the Reciprocal Identity for the cosecant function (<xref ref="def_reciprocal-identities"/>) is given by:
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>\csc x=\frac{1}{\sin x}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      When <m>\sin x=0</m>, corresponding to <m>x=\ldots,-\pi,0,\pi,2\pi,\ldots</m>, the denominator becomes zero, leading to vertical asympototes. In general, <m>\csc x</m> is undefined for angles of the form <m>n\pi</m>, where <m>n</m> is an integer.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since we learned in <xref ref="subsec_periodic-functions"/> that the cosecant function is periodic with a period of <m>2\pi</m>, we can focus on one period, such as <m>0\lt x \lt2\pi</m>, and repeat the pattern. In this interval, we have vertical asymptotes at <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=\pi</m>, and <m>x=2\pi</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      As <m>x</m> approaches zero, sine is a small number nearing zero, causing cosecant to become large, approaching positive infinity. When <m>x</m> increases towards <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>,  sine increases to <m>1</m>, and cosecant decreases to <m>1</m>. As <m>x</m> moves from <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> to <m>\pi</m> sine approaches zero, and cosecant approaches infinity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Similarly, for <m>x\gt\pi</m>, nearing <m>\pi</m>, sine is a small, negative number near zero, resulting in cosecant becoming a large negative number, approaching negative infinity. As <m>x</m> increases to <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, sine decreases to <m>-1</m>, and cosecant increases to <m>-1</m>. Finally, as <m>x</m> moves from <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m> to <m>2\pi</m>,  sine once again approaches a small negative number, causing cosecant to approach negative infinity. This behavior is shown in <xref ref="cosecant-graph-animation"/>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="cosecant-graph-animation">
      <caption>
        As <m>\theta</m> moves from <m>0^{\circ}</m> to <m>360^{\circ}</m>, this figure plots the values of <m>y=\sin x</m> and <m>y = \csc \theta</m>. Note that while we will generally be using radians when graphing trigonometric functions, this figure uses degrees to help visualize the angle.
      </caption>
      <interactive geogebra="b4zc4xwu" aspect="1.75:0.75"/>
    </figure>
