  <p>
    Recall that if <m>\theta</m> is an angle with radian measure <m>t</m>, then the <term>six trigonometric functions</term> become
    <md>
      <mrow>\sin \theta\amp =y \amp  \cos \theta\amp =x \amp  \tan \theta\amp =\frac{y}{x}  (x\neq0)</mrow>
      <mrow>\csc \theta\amp =\frac{1}{y}  (y\neq0) \amp  \sec \theta\amp =\frac{1}{x}  (x\neq0) \amp  \cot \theta\amp =\frac{x}{y}  (y\neq0)</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <image xml:id="fig-unitcircle-theta" width="50%">
  <latex-image>
  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.5]
  \draw[&lt;->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
  \draw[&lt;->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
  \draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
  \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (45:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.2cm] {1};
  \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0.707106781187,0) node[midway,below] {$x$};
  \draw[line width=2pt] (0.707106781187,0) -- (0.707106781187,0.707106781187) node[midway,right] {$y$};
  \filldraw[black] (45:1cm) circle(1pt) node[above right] {\(P(x,y)\)};
  \draw ([shift=(0:0.25cm)]0,0) arc (0:45:0.25cm) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm,yshift=0.1cm] {\(\theta\)};
  \end{tikzpicture}
  </latex-image>
  </image>
  <p>
    Division is not required for the trigonometric functions <m>\sin\theta</m> and <m>\cos\theta</m> and so we do not need to worry about dividing by zero,
    thus <m>\theta</m> can be any angle. In other words, the domains for <m>\sin\theta</m> and <m>\cos\theta</m> consist of the set of all real numbers.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, looking at <m>\tan\theta</m> and <m>\sec\theta</m>, you may notice there is division by <m>x</m>. We run into problems when the denominator is zero, in other words, <m>x=0</m> would result in dividing by 0. These are the points when the terminal side of <m>\theta</m> lies on the <m>y</m>-axis. On the unit circle, the points are <m>(0,1)</m> and <m>(0,-1)</m>. These points correspond to the angles <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> and<m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, as well as all their coterminal angles:
    <m>\ldots, -\frac{3\pi}{2}, \frac{-\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{3\pi}{2}, \frac{5\pi}{2}, \ldots</m>. In general, any angle of the form
    <m>\frac{\pi}{2}+n\pi</m> for some integer <m>n</m> should be excluded from the domain.
  </p>
  <p>
    Similarly, we run into problems for <m>\csc\theta</m> and <m>\cot\theta</m> when <m>y=0</m> since we would divide by 0. This corresponds to when the terminal side of <m>\theta</m> lies on the <m>x</m>-axis. These points on the unit circle are <m>(1,0)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m> and have corresponding angles <m>0</m> and <m>\pi</m>, as well as all their coterminal angles: <m>\ldots, -2\pi, -\pi, 0, \pi, 2\pi, \ldots</m>. In general, any angle of the form <m>\pi\cdot n</m> for some integer <m>n</m> should be excluded from the domain.
  </p>
